This is why, ultimately, I am comfortable with the implications of my frame=
work, and why I think the answer to the remedy question is an injunction ag=
ainst Google making any sort of payments or revenue share for search; if yo=
u=E2=80=99re a monopoly you don=E2=80=99t get to extend your advantage with=
 contracts, period (now do most-favored nation clauses). More broadly, we t=
end to think of monopolies as being mean; the problem with Aggregators is t=
hey have the temptation to be too nice. It has been very profitable to be G=
oogle=E2=80=99s friend; I think consumers =E2=80=94 and Google =E2=80=94 ar=
e better off if the company has a few more enemies.

This is a remedy that is arguably unfair =E2=80=94 would Microsoft be able =
to do a revenue share for Bing? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is at least straightf=
orward and directly connected to the violation at hand. That, though, is ap=
parently not enough for the Justice Department: instead of identifying a pr=
oblem and seeking to solve it, they are interpreting this case as an invita=
tion to carve up a company they don=E2=80=99t like. The fact of the matter =
is that Google built Chrome, and they built it well, and that is not and sh=
ould not be a crime.

Search Data
-----------

Most of the headlines focused on Chrome =E2=80=94 that=E2=80=99s partly why=
 I started there =E2=80=94 but the search data aspect is arguably a bigger =
deal. From that Bloomberg article:

Regarding data licensing, the antitrust enforcers plan to propose two optio=
ns: That Google sell the underlying =E2=80=9Cclick and query=E2=80=9D data =
and also separately syndicate its search results, according to the people. =
The company currently sells syndicated search results, but with restriction=
s, such as preventing their use on mobile. Forcing Google to syndicate its =
search results would allow rival search engines and AI startups to quickly =
improve their quality, while the data feed would allow others to build thei=
r own search index.

This is the relevant paragraph in the DOJ=E2=80=99s October filing ( https:=
//storage.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.dcd.223205/gov.uscourts.dcd.=
223205.1052.0_5.pdf ) about potential remedies:

Virtually every component and process of a general search engine benefits f=
rom data=E2=80=A6Google=E2=80=99s unlawful behavior has enabled it to accum=
ulate and use data at the expense of rivals. Accordingly, Plaintiffs are co=
nsidering remedies that will offset this advantage and strengthen competiti=
on by requiring, among other things, Google to make available, in whole or =
through an API, (1) the indexes, data, feeds, and models used for Google se=
arch, including those used in AI-assisted search features, and (2) Google s=
earch results, features, and ads, including the underlying ranking signals,=
 especially on mobile. Plaintiffs are mindful of potential user privacy con=
cerns in the context of data sharing; however, genuine privacy concerns mus=
t be distinguished from pretextual arguments to maintain market position or=
 deny scale to rivals. As a result, Plaintiffs are considering remedies tha=
t would prohibit Google from using or retaining data that cannot be effecti=
vely shared with others on the basis of privacy concerns. Plaintiffs are al=
so considering other remedies that would reduce the cost and complexity of =
indexing or retaining data for rival general search engines.

The Bloomberg report does suggest that the final request has been somewhat =
narrowed; the initial filing, particularly the access to Google=E2=80=99s i=
ndex, would allow rivals to not only have search as good as Google, but als=
o to present it in the interface of their choosing. Access to search result=
s is less valuable, but certainly not nothing; ironically, this would proba=
bly result in a situation where there is only one search engine: why would,=
 say, Microsoft or any of its customers invest in building an alternative w=
hen they could just use Google=E2=80=99s results?

Once again, however, the biggest winner would probably be Meta. I barely me=
ntioned search in Meta=E2=80=99s AI Abundance ( https://stratechery.com/202=
4/metas-ai-abundance/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZW=
NoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5w=
YXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InV=
yaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L21ldGFzLWFpLWFidW5kYW5jZS8iXX=
0sImV4cCI6MTczNDcwMDI3NiwiaWF0IjoxNzMyMTA4Mjc2LCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wY=
XNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNz=
ZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHB=
XSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.q-GjoX-0AI4F6XUyW5Latz5kZwjroblhj3KOi_T=
c542v80YQixGPAcqsBiaQ-QojoPSrkjUZkFfje0G3kRgKv2X2z1OtMIdAR_mCI8uDVOf5JqO6fY=
SOiMKoL1V6nWx9MjTEcBWwKktZHTp7NuDCc_aaezgnDTeMVAe3Co7v0r2t9iHpLvUIuST-_83hl=
