MwlGF8tQi_h_SQ3xafSruzhJx9BkN4SaXZwIsNraHQAnECeZGmngMVzI68wPoGyKMoNiRLFFODt=
WZA ) , but if there is one company who would benefit not just from Google =
search results but also Google=E2=80=99s click and query data =E2=80=94 wha=
t results people click on =E2=80=94 it would be Meta, the only Data Factory=
 that rivals Google. And, frankly, that would be unfair. Yes, I get the arg=
ument that Google has some amount of data it wouldn=E2=80=99t have otherwis=
e because of the payments it made to Apple and others, but again, I think t=
hat Google would dominate those search surfaces regardless; the crime was i=
n paying off a competitor, and demanding that Google give away the result o=
f nearly three decades of development and innovation =E2=80=94 instead of s=
imply addressing the problem at hand =E2=80=94 is too much.

EU Fines Meta
-------------

From the Financial Times ( https://www.ft.com/content/8dc18484-ee7d-4008-95=
dc-cc76320441ab ) :

Meta has been fined nearly =E2=82=AC800mn by Brussels after regulators accu=
sed Facebook=E2=80=99s parent company of stifling competition by =E2=80=9Ct=
ying=E2=80=9D its free Marketplace services with the social network. Margre=
the Vestager, the EU=E2=80=99s outgoing competition chief, said on Thursday=
 that by linking Facebook with its classified ads service Meta had =E2=80=
=9Cimposed unfair trading conditions=E2=80=9D on other providers. She added=
: =E2=80=9CIt did so to benefit its own service Facebook Marketplace, there=
by giving it advantages that [others] could not match. This is illegal.=E2=
=80=9D

Meta said it would appeal against the =E2=82=AC797.72mn fine levied by regu=
lators. =E2=80=9CWe built Marketplace in response to consumer demand =E2=80=
=94 this decision ignores the market realities, and will only serve to prot=
ect incumbent marketplaces from competition.=E2=80=9D It added: =E2=80=9CTh=
e European Commission=E2=80=99s decision provides no evidence of competitiv=
e harm to rivals or any harm to consumers.=E2=80=9D

Unfortunately for Meta, the E.U. doesn=E2=80=99t care about consumers. Meta=
 did what one might think we want companies to do: they built instead of bo=
ught. Moreover, they built a product that was far better than something lik=
e, say, Craigslist, because it was tied into Facebook itself. That meant yo=
u could know who you were buying from, message with them, etc., all of whic=
h the E.U. deemed illegal.

I=E2=80=99ve already gone long, so I don=E2=80=99t want to dwell on this ca=
se too much, other than to point out the similarity in attitude between the=
 DOJ in the Google case and the EU with Facebook: it=E2=80=99s not enough t=
o identify and correct uncompetitive behavior; what both regulators wish to=
 do is diminish and destroy the value of what has already been built, with =
nary a consideration about whether consumers benefit or not. It does, frank=
ly, explain why I=E2=80=99ve done basically a 180 on antitrust enforcement =
generally: there are a lot of problems with big tech, and genuine abuse, bu=
t if the remedies are fueled by animus about success I want off the train.

